Dijkstra's algorithm is used to find the shortest path between nodes in a weighted graph. Here's an example of a graph that can be traversed using Dijkstra's algorithm:

```
A --1-- B --2-- C
 \      |       /
  \     |      /
   4   3      /
    \  |     /
     \ |    /
       D --5-- E
```

In this graph, the nodes are A, B, C, D, and E, and the numbers are the weights of the edges between nodes. Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest path between A and E.

Here's how you can implement Dijkstra's algorithm in Java:

```java
import java.util.*;

public class Dijkstra {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define the graph as an adjacency list
        Map<String, List<Edge>> graph = new HashMap<>();
        graph.put("A", Arrays.asList(new Edge("B", 1), new Edge("D", 4)));
        graph.put("B", Arrays.asList(new Edge("A", 1), new Edge("C", 2), new Edge("D", 3)));
        graph.put("C", Arrays.asList(new Edge("B", 2), new Edge("E", 5)));
        graph.put("D", Arrays.asList(new Edge("A", 4), new Edge("B", 3), new Edge("E", 5)));
        graph.put("E", Arrays.asList(new Edge("C", 5), new Edge("D", 5)));

        String start = "A";
        String end = "E";
        Map<String, Integer> shortestPaths = dijkstra(graph, start);

        System.out.println("Shortest path from " + start + " to " + end + " is " + shortestPaths.get(end));
    }

    public static Map<String, Integer> dijkstra(Map<String, List<Edge>> graph, String start) {
        Map<String, Integer> distances = new HashMap<>();
        Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
        Queue<Node> queue = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.comparingInt(node -> node.cost));

        for (String vertex : graph.keySet()) {
            distances.put(vertex, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        }

        distances.put(start, 0);
        queue.add(new Node(start, 0));

        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            Node currentNode = queue.poll();
            String currentVertex = currentNode.vertex;

            if (visited.contains(currentVertex)) continue;
            visited.add(currentVertex);

            for (Edge edge : graph.get(currentVertex)) {
                String neighbor = edge.to;
                int edgeWeight = edge.weight;

                int updatedDistance = distances.get(currentVertex) + edgeWeight;
                if (updatedDistance < distances.get(neighbor)) {
                    distances.put(neighbor, updatedDistance);
                    queue.add(new Node(neighbor, updatedDistance));
                }
            }
        }

        return distances;
    }

    static class Edge {
        String to;
        int weight;

        public Edge(String to, int weight) {
            this.to = to;
            this.weight = weight;
        }
    }

    static class Node {
        String vertex;
        int cost;

        public Node(String vertex, int cost) {
            this.vertex = vertex;
            this.cost = cost;
        }
    }
}
```

This implementation defines the graph as an adjacency list, and it uses a priority queue to efficiently select the next node to visit. The main function calculates the shortest paths between the start node and all other nodes in the graph. The result is a map that shows the shortest path between the start node and each other node in the graph. In this example, the shortest path between A and E is 6 (A -> B -> D -> E).
